<subSubSection pageId="52" pageNumber="53" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="52.[151,1436,152,476]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,335,301,327]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Discussion.</emphasis>
In 
<bibRefCitation author="Crosskey, R. W." box="[376,591,301,327]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" pagination="393 - 551" refId="ref53854" refString="Crosskey, R. W. (1962) A revision of the genus Pygophora Schiner (Diptera, Muscidae). Transactions of the Zoological Society of London, 29, 393 - 551." type="journal article" year="1962">Crosskey’s (1962)</bibRefCitation>
key, the new species runs to couplet 24 and differs from the species in that couplet by the absence of scales or scale-like setae on tergite 5.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="52" pageNumber="53" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="52.[151,1436,152,476]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,337,375,401]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name comes from the Latin words 
<emphasis box="[801,864,376,401]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">spina</emphasis>
, meaning “spine” and 
<emphasis box="[1130,1186,376,401]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">ferre</emphasis>
, “to bear”, and refers to the numerous spinose setae on male abdomen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
